{"title_page": "Katie Bray", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name          = Katie Bray\n| birth_name    = Katie Emily Bray\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date and age|1987|01|23}}\n| birth_place   = [[Exeter]], England\n| nationality   = English\n| occupation    = Operatic mezzo-soprano\n| alma_mater    = {{plainlist|\n* [[University of Manchester]]\n* [[Royal Academy of Music]] \n}}\n| years_active  = 2012 - present\n| awards        = {{plainlist|\n* [[BBC Cardiff Singer of the World competition|BBC Cardiff Singer of the World]]|\n}}\n}}\n\n'''Katie Emily Bray''' (born January 23, 1987) is an English [[mezzo-soprano]] and is best known as the winner of the Dame Joan Sutherland Audience Prize at the [[BBC Cardiff Singer of the World competition|BBC Cardiff Singer of the World]] in 2019. She is particularly noted for her baroque repertoire.<ref name=\"Ray\"/>\n\n==Early life and education==\n[[File:St Margaret's School, Exeter - geograph.org.uk - 1638687.jpg|thumb|St Margaret's School, Exeter]]\nBray was born on 23 January 1987 in [[Exeter]], [[Devon]], England. She was educated at St Margaret's School in Exeter until 2005 and went on to study at the [[University of Manchester]], graduating in 2008. She then went onto study opera as a post-graduate at the [[Royal Academy of Music]], where she was taught by Elizabeth Ritchie and Iain Ledingham,<ref name=\"BBC\"/><ref name=\"Linn\">{{cite web |url= https://www.linnrecords.com/artist-katie-bray|publisher= [[Linn Records]]|title= Katie Bray|accessdate=2020-04-04}}</ref> and finished her studies at the academy in 2012 having won an Alfred Alexander Scholarship and recipient of The Karaviotis Scholarship<ref name=\"BBC\">{{cite web |url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/profiles/3LnNm0wbFsgPsSx8PX1SnW0/katie-bray|publisher= [[BBC]]|title= Katie Bray|accessdate=2020-04-04}}</ref>\n\n==Professional career==\n\nIn 2013, Bray made her debuts with [[Glyndebourne Festival Opera]] and [[English Touring Opera]].<ref name=\"Linn\"/> Bray has also performed with [[Opera North]], [[English National Opera]], [[Scottish Opera]], [[Welsh National Opera]], [[Garsington Opera]], [[Opera Holland Park]], [[English Touring Opera]] and [[Irish National Opera]].<ref name=\"Ray\">{{cite web |url= http://www.rayfieldallied.com/artists/katie-bray|publisher= Rayfield Allied|title= Katie Bray (Mezzo-soprano)|accessdate=2020-04-04}}</ref> Bray has also performed in concert halls and festivals around the United Kingdom, such as [[Wigmore Hall]], [[Cadogan Hall]], the [[Holywell Music Room]] and [[St George's Hanover Square Church|St George's, Hanover Square]]. She has also performed recitals in many song festivals that include the [[City of London Festival]], the London English Song Festival and the [[Oxford Lieder Festival]].<ref name=\"Ray\"/>\n\n==Competitions and awards==\n\nBray has won many singing competitions and awards, including:\n* Alfred Alexander Scholarship and recipient of The Karaviotis Scholarship<ref name=\"Somerset\"/>\n* Major van Someren-Godfrey Prize for English Song (2009)<ref name=\"Somerset\">{{cite web |url= http://www.somersetchamberchoir.performers.co.uk/Wells12_prog.pdf|publisher= Somerset Chamber Choir|title= Mozart mass in C minor|accessdate=2020-04-04}}</ref> \n* Elena Gerhardt Lieder Prize (2010)<ref name=\"Somerset\"/> \n* Audience Prize in the Handel Singing Competition (2010)<ref name=\"Somerset\"/> \n* Third prize in the Jackdaws Vocal Award (2010)<ref name=\"Somerset\"/> \n* Sir Thomas Armstrong Prize<ref name=\"Somerset\"/> \n* Opera Prize in the Mozart International Singing Competition (2011)<ref name=\"Somerset\"/>\n* Third prize overall in Mozart International Singing Competition (2011)<ref name=\"Somerset\"/>\n* At the Royal Academy of Music she received the Principal's Prize and first prize in the Richard Lewis Singing Competition (2011)<ref name=\"RAM\">{{cite web |url= https://www.ram.ac.uk/departments/vocal/richard-lewis-award|publisher= [[Royal Academy of Music]]|title= Richard Lewis Award|accessdate=2020-04-04}}</ref> \n* Represented England in the [[BBC Cardiff Singer of the World competition]], where she won the Dame Joan Sutherland Audience Prize (2019)<ref name=\"BBC\"/>\n\n==Discography==\nBray appears on \n* ''David Matthews: Symphony No. 7 & Vespers'' (2014)<ref name=\"AllMusic\">{{cite web |url= https://www.allmusic.com/artist/katie-bray-mn0003211227/discography\n|publisher= [[AllMusic]]|title= Katie Bray - Biography by Blair Sanderson|accessdate=2020-04-04}}</ref>\n* ''Mahler: Lieder eines fahrenden Gesellen (arr. Schoenberg)'' (2015)<ref name=\"All\">{{cite web |url= https://www.allmusic.com/album/release/mahler-lieder-eines-fahrenden-gesellen-arr-schoenberg-mr0004398365|publisher= [[AllMusic]]|title= Mahler: Lieder eines fahrenden Gesellen (arr. Schoenberg)|accessdate=2020-04-04}}</ref> \n* ''R\u00fcckert Lieder: Robert & Clara Schumann'' (2016)<ref name=\"AllMusic\"/>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of Royal Academy of Music people]]\n*[[List of mezzo-sopranos in non-classical music]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{cite web |url= https://www.bach-cantatas.com/Bio/Bray-Katie.htm|publisher= Bach Cantatas Website|title= Katie Bray (Mezzo-soprano)|accessdate=2020-04-04}}\n\n{{BBC Cardiff Singer of the World competition|state=collapsed}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bray, Katie}}\n[[Category:1987 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Devon]]\n[[Category:Operatic mezzo-sopranos]]\n[[Category:English opera singers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name          = Katie Bray\n| birth_name    = Katie Emily Bray\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date and age|1987|01|23}}\n| birth_place   = [[Exeter]], England\n| nationality   = English\n| occupation    = Operatic mezzo-soprano\n| alma_mater    = {{plainlist|\n* [[University of Manchester]]\n* [[Royal Academy of Music]] \n}}\n| years_active  = 2012 to date\n| awards        = {{plainlist|\n* [[BBC Cardiff Singer of the World competition|BBC Cardiff Singer of the World]]|\n}}\n}}\n\n'''Katie Emily Bray''' (born January 23, 1987) is an English [[mezzo-soprano]] and is best known as the winner of the Dame Joan Sutherland Audience Prize at the [[BBC Cardiff Singer of the World competition|BBC Cardiff Singer of the World]] in 2019. She is particularly noted for her baroque repertoire.<ref name=\"Ray\"/>\n\n==Early life and education==\n[[File:St Margaret's School, Exeter - geograph.org.uk - 1638687.jpg|thumb|St Margaret's School, Exeter]]\nBray was born on 23 January 1987 in [[Exeter]], [[Devon]], England. She was educated at St Margaret's School in Exeter until 2005 and went on to study at the [[University of Manchester]], graduating in 2008. She then went onto study opera as a post-graduate at the [[Royal Academy of Music]], where she was taught by Elizabeth Ritchie and Iain Ledingham,<ref name=\"BBC\"/><ref name=\"Linn\">{{cite web |url= https://www.linnrecords.com/artist-katie-bray|publisher= [[Linn Records]]|title= Katie Bray|accessdate=2020-04-04}}</ref> and finished her studies at the academy in 2012 having won an Alfred Alexander Scholarship and recipient of The Karaviotis Scholarship<ref name=\"BBC\">{{cite web |url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/profiles/3LnNm0wbFsgPsSx8PX1SnW0/katie-bray|publisher= [[BBC]]|title= Katie Bray|accessdate=2020-04-04}}</ref>\n\n==Professional career==\n\nIn 2013, Bray made her debuts with [[Glyndebourne Festival Opera]] and [[English Touring Opera]].<ref name=\"Linn\"/> Bray has also performed with [[Opera North]], [[English National Opera]], [[Scottish Opera]], [[Welsh National Opera]], [[Garsington Opera]], [[Opera Holland Park]], [[English Touring Opera]] and [[Irish National Opera]].<ref name=\"Ray\">{{cite web |url= http://www.rayfieldallied.com/artists/katie-bray|publisher= Rayfield Allied|title= Katie Bray (Mezzo-soprano)|accessdate=2020-04-04}}</ref> Bray has also performed in concert halls and festivals around the United Kingdom, such as [[Wigmore Hall]], [[Cadogan Hall]], the [[Holywell Music Room]] and [[St George's Hanover Square Church|St George's, Hanover Square]]. She has also performed recitals in many song festivals that include the [[City of London Festival]], the London English Song Festival and the [[Oxford Lieder Festival]].<ref name=\"Ray\"/>\n\n==Competitions and awards==\n\nBray has won many singing competitions and awards, including:\n* Alfred Alexander Scholarship and recipient of The Karaviotis Scholarship<ref name=\"Somerset\"/>\n* Major van Someren-Godfrey Prize for English Song (2009)<ref name=\"Somerset\">{{cite web |url= http://www.somersetchamberchoir.performers.co.uk/Wells12_prog.pdf|publisher= Somerset Chamber Choir|title= Mozart mass in C minor|accessdate=2020-04-04}}</ref> \n* Elena Gerhardt Lieder Prize (2010)<ref name=\"Somerset\"/> \n* Audience Prize in the Handel Singing Competition (2010)<ref name=\"Somerset\"/> \n* Third prize in the Jackdaws Vocal Award (2010)<ref name=\"Somerset\"/> \n* Sir Thomas Armstrong Prize<ref name=\"Somerset\"/> \n* Opera Prize in the Mozart International Singing Competition (2011)<ref name=\"Somerset\"/>\n* Third prize overall in Mozart International Singing Competition (2011)<ref name=\"Somerset\"/>\n* At the Royal Academy of Music she received the Principal's Prize and first prize in the Richard Lewis Singing Competition (2011)<ref name=\"RAM\">{{cite web |url= https://www.ram.ac.uk/departments/vocal/richard-lewis-award|publisher= [[Royal Academy of Music]]|title= Richard Lewis Award|accessdate=2020-04-04}}</ref> \n* Represented England in the [[BBC Cardiff Singer of the World competition]], where she won the Dame Joan Sutherland Audience Prize (2019)<ref name=\"BBC\"/>\n\n==Discography==\nBray appears on \n* ''David Matthews: Symphony No. 7 & Vespers'' (2014)<ref name=\"AllMusic\">{{cite web |url= https://www.allmusic.com/artist/katie-bray-mn0003211227/discography\n|publisher= [[AllMusic]]|title= Katie Bray - Biography by Blair Sanderson|accessdate=2020-04-04}}</ref>\n* ''Mahler: Lieder eines fahrenden Gesellen (arr. Schoenberg)'' (2015)<ref name=\"All\">{{cite web |url= https://www.allmusic.com/album/release/mahler-lieder-eines-fahrenden-gesellen-arr-schoenberg-mr0004398365|publisher= [[AllMusic]]|title= Mahler: Lieder eines fahrenden Gesellen (arr. Schoenberg)|accessdate=2020-04-04}}</ref> \n* ''R\u00fcckert Lieder: Robert & Clara Schumann'' (2016)<ref name=\"AllMusic\"/>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of Royal Academy of Music people]]\n*[[List of mezzo-sopranos in non-classical music]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{cite web |url= https://www.bach-cantatas.com/Bio/Bray-Katie.htm|publisher= Bach Cantatas Website|title= Katie Bray (Mezzo-soprano)|accessdate=2020-04-04}}\n\n{{BBC Cardiff Singer of the World competition|state=collapsed}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bray, Katie}}\n[[Category:1987 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Devon]]\n[[Category:Operatic mezzo-sopranos]]\n[[Category:English opera singers]]\n", "name_user": "Rfl0216", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Katie_Bray"}
