dership elections#1998 leadership election results|October 17, 1998]]\n| party3 = {{Canadian party colour|MB|Liberal|name}}\n| leaders_seat3 = [[River Heights (electoral district)|River Heights]]\n| last_election3 = 1\n| seats3 = 2\n| seat_change3 = {{increase}}1\n| popular_vote3 = 52,123\n| percentage3 = 13.19%\n| swing3 = {{decrease}}0.21[[Percentage point|pp]]\n| map_image = Manitoba_general_election_2003_-_Results_By_Riding.svg\n| map_size = 400px\n| map_caption = Popular vote by riding. As this is an FPTP election, seat totals are not determined by popular vote, but instead via results by each riding. Click the map for more details.\n| title = Premier\n| posttitle = Premier after election\n| before_election = Gary Doer\n| before_party = {{Canadian party colour|MB|NDP|name}}\n| after_election = Gary Doer\n| after_party = {{Canadian party colour|MB|NDP|name}}\n}}\nThe '''2003 Manitoba general election''' was held on June 3, 2003 to elect Members of the [[Legislative Assembly of Manitoba|Legislative Assembly]] of the Province of [[Manitoba]], Canada. It was won by the [[New Democratic Party of Manitoba|New Democratic Party]], which won 35 seats out of 57.  The [[Progressive Conservative Party of Manitoba|Progressive Conservative Party]] finished second with twenty seats.  The [[Manitoba Liberal Party|Liberal Party]] won two seats.\n{{clear left}}\n\n==Results==\n{{Electiontable|Manitoba general election, 2003}}'''Summary of the June 3, 2003 [[Manitoba Legislature]] election results'''\n|- style=\"background:#ccc;\"\n! rowspan=\"2\" colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:left;\"|Party\n! rowspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:left;\"|Party leader\n!rowspan=\"2\"|<span style=\"font-size: 80%;\">Candidates</span>\n! colspan=\"4\" style=\"text-align:center;\"|Seats\n! colspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align:center;\"|Popular vote\n|- style=\"background:#ccc;\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1999\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Dissolution of parliament|<span style=\"font-size: 80%;\"